%N A372265 a(n) = floor((2*n - 3 + sqrt(1 + 4*n!))/2).
%C A372265 Information-theoretic bound on the largest card deck with which one can perform an n-card trick, when the assistant chooses two cards to hide.
%C A372265 The bound is based on the following argument: The assistant has n choose 2 ways to pick the hidden cards and (n-2)! ways to arrange the rest of the cards. The number of strategies can't be smaller than the number of potential guesses by the magician which is d - n + 2 choose 2, where d is the deck size.
%H A372265 Aria Chen, Tyler Cummins, Rishi De Francesco, Jate Greene, Tanya Khovanova, Alexander Meng, Tanish Parida, Anirudh Pulugurtha, Anand Swaroop, and Samuel Tsui, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2405.21007">Card Tricks and Information</a>, arXiv:2405.21007 [math.HO], 2024. See p. 21.
%H A372265 Michael Kleber and Ravi Vakil, <a href="https://web.northeastern.edu/seigen/11Magic/Articles/Best%20Card%20Trick.pdf">The best card trick</a>, The Mathematical Intelligencer 24 (2002), 9-11.
%e A372265 For n=3, the equation on the deck size becomes the following: d-1 choose 2 can't exceed 3. Thus, a(3) = 4.
%t A372265 Table[Floor[(2 n - 3 + Sqrt[1 + 4 n!])/2], {n, 30}]
